National Suicide Prevention Week
You don’t have to be a mental health professional to make a difference in our schools and community. Knowing the signs and symptoms of suicide and how to help that person reach out for help - can save a life.

Here are several resources:
https://afsp.org/teens-and-suicide-what-parents-should-know

https://afsp.org/suicide-prevention-resources

Have additional questions? Please reach out to your child’s School Counselor. School Counselors are highly trained to help support you and your child through the conversation and can provide local resources if additional support is needed.

post_text:
National Suicide Prevention
What is SEL?
As we protect our mental health and cope with the unknown, it is essential to learn and practice healthy skills to manage everyday life. Dodge City Public Schools believes in teaching our students social-emotional skills that promote positive wellbeing. Last year, K-12 students learned about the Zones of Regulation, which gave them a common vocabulary to help identify emotions and healthy skills to regulate responses. Students learned self-efficacy and how to trust their abilities to perform and achieve their goals.
This year, our K-12 SEL focus is on self-regulation. Students will learn how to be proactive in their choices to achieve their goals.
Talk to your student about ways they can self-regulate, and what might be a self-regulation goal for their future? Examples: save money to buy something they want, limit the time they spend gaming, obtain a part-time job, join a club or activity, etc.

post_text:
2020 National Suicide Prevention Week

Social connection is the theme for today. In a time where everyone seems connected by technology, people can still feel loneliness and isolation. Spending time by oneself short term is a great way to relax, regroup, reflect, and rest. However, connecting with others is vital to our mental health. One of our DCHS TALC students made a video last spring. It is an excellent example of ideas to start that positive social connection at home.
What can you do to reach out and connect safely to someone today?

Want to participate in a fun social connection activity with family or friends? As a family or physically distanced small group, paint an inspiring message on a rock and add it to the community rock garden in Eisenhower Park, 205 Gunsmoke St - Downtown, Dodge City. DCHS TALC Teen Yellow Ribbon Group started this rock garden. Add a rock, take a rock!

Dr. Dierksen receives 2020 UCEA Excellence in Education Leadership Award. This award is an annual recognition for practicing school administrators who have made significant contributions to the improvement of administrator preparation.

The Dodge City/Garden City Education Leadership Academy was recognized as an outstanding example of collaboration and program success. Dr. Steve Karlin, Garden City Public Schools and Dr. Fred Dierksen, Dodge City Public Schools were co-recipients for 2020 UCEA Excellence in Education Leadership Award.

Dr. Donna Augustine-Shaw and Dr. Jerry Johnson from Kansas State University presented the award during USD 443 Board of Education Meeting.

post_text:
July 27, 2020

Dodge City, KS – USD 443 BOE votes 6 to 1 for student start date on August 25. Teachers will report on August 17.

According to Dr. Dierksen, “It’s time to start school. We prefer to have face to face instruction, but we also have the option of Remote Live Learning. " We want our parents to feel comfortable with their choices."

Making this decision is a tremendous responsibility, but prolonging the start of school will not mitigate COVID -19. It will take our entire community working together and following protocols so that our schools can stay open for the school year. In our homes, we can practice how to wear face coverings, good hygiene, and limit outside travel.

Seventy-eight percent of USD 443 teachers responded to the district survey asking if teachers were able to conduct face-to-face instruction; ninety-five percent said yes. Those who responded no because of health concerns may have the option to teach online.

The Return to School plan will be presented for approval at the next board meeting on August 10, 2020.

This family gets a very big shout out!! Every day, EVERY day since March 23rd, this family has walked over one mile one way to the literacy bus to get grab & go meals! So they average almost 3 miles total every day to get meals! (They missed one day at Easter Break.) That’s 84 days they have done this for a total of 252 miles!!!! And they’re not done! They have walked through windy & rainy & cold & hot weather, never once complaining, & always with a smile on their faces. They are very grateful & thankful for the meals that they have received! Thank you to the mom, Brenda, & her kids Leda, Hasheem, & Arin! We appreciate you & all you do! It is an honor & privilege for us to serve you! #EEII #dcpsproud

This afternoon, Gov. Kelly released more information on the executive orders for re-opening schools for the 20-21 school year.
Executive Order 20-58 pushes the start of public schools until after Labor Day. The Kansas Board of Education must vote on this issue; they are planning to meet about the governor's orders on Wednesday.

Executive Order 20-59 addresses face coverings for all students, staff, and visitors: social distancing protocols, and temperature checks.
USD 443 is planning to follow the State Board and Governor's Executive Orders. Currently, we are waiting for clarification.

Each decision significantly affects our district and our re-opening plans. We will do our best to provide you with updates as we receive them.

Queridos Padres y Guardianes,
Este comunicado es para dejarles saber que estamos muy emocionados por el inicio próximo del año escolar. En efecto es desafiante preparase para el día de apertura cunado aún hay incertidumbre debido a COVID-19. Sin embargo, estamos trabajando para hacer las mejores acomodaciones para nuestros estudiantes y trabajadores y mantenernos seguros y saludables. La importancia de instrucción académica para dodo los niños es fundamental para su desarrollo y su bienestar, por eso estamos preparados para ser flexibles con nuestros planes de educación. Nuestra prioridad número uno es mantener la salud de nuestros estudiantes, familias y comunidades. Estaremos incorporando recomendaciones del estado y del condado para nuestro distrito. Estaremos trabajando para mantenerlos informados acerca de los planes de apertura de DCPS y situaciones de COVID en la página del distrito escolar, redes sociales y correo electrónico del distrito.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,
We are reaching out to let you know how excited we are for the upcoming school year. Indeed, it is challenging to prepare for opening day when there is still uncertainty due to COVID-19. However, we are working to make the best accommodations for our students and staff and keep us as safe as possible. The importance of academic instruction for all children is fundamental for their development and well-being, so we are prepared to be flexible with our education plans. It is our top priority to support the overall health of our students, families, and communities. We will be incorporating the state and county recommendations for our district. We will work to keep you informed of DCPS Reopening Plans and COVID situations on the district website, social media channels and district email.

If you are new to Dodge City or if you have a child that will be in kindergarten starting this fall, these are the steps you need to follow to enroll them in school.

1. Call First Stop Enrollment at 620-471-2117 for an appointment. You will need to bring a birth certificate, immunization record, social security number (optional), and a physical is required for students under age 9 or those enrolling for the first time.

2. Call our Technology Department at 620-371-1080 to set up a Skyward Family Access account.

3. Now you are ready to enroll your child.

Starting JULY 13, you can go to usd443.org/Enrollment.
If you prefer to enroll on-site, that option will be available August 4-6 at the Civic Center.

As DCPS deals with ongoing uncertainty around the current COVID-19 pandemic, it’s important to remember that we all play a role in promoting prevention.
Today, we received notification of the confirmed COVID-19 case in one of our childcare rooms at Bright Beginnings. We are following recommendations by KDHE and Ford County Health Department. In compliance with these guidelines, we are closing one childcare room from June 19 through June 29.
Staff from Bright Beginnings have communicated with all parents potentially affected by this case.

post_text:
EXPANDED ELIGIBILITY TO SNAP DURING THE COVID-19 PANDEMIC:
What the changes to food assistance means for hungry Kansans

SNAP Overview
The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), formerly known as “food stamps,” is the largest food assistance program administered by the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA). SNAP is one of the primary ways we address hunger, malnutrition, and poverty in the United States. SNAP plays an essential role in reducing food insecurity and improving the health of our hungry neighbors. In Kansas, SNAP is administered by the Department for Children and Families.

In this video series, Pamela Ramos, 8th grade Social Studies teacher at DCMS, talks about her 1800s Curriculum. She created a three part video series demonstrating an Antebellum dress she had made.

The first video, she introduces herself and talks a little bit about the dress.

The second video, she talks about each piece of the dress and how they come together.

The third video, she models the dress.

If you would like her to come to your class, next year, to talk about and show her dress, she shares her contact information at the end of the the video series.

post_text:
Dodge City Public Schools received notification by Ford County Health Department this afternoon that one kitchen staff employee at Ross Elementary tested positive for COVID-19 (Coronavirus).
School officials, as directed by Ford County Health Department and the Kansas Department of Health and Environment, quarantined all kitchen staff working at Ross. As an added safety precaution, school officials also quarantined the custodians on duty at Ross.

Lunches will be prepared off-site and delivered to Ross Elementary as a distribution point. Therefore, meals may still be picked up Ross Elementary as scheduled.

Our top priority is the health and safety of our students, staff, and families. We will continue to provide updates as they relate to school operations through the district website, email and social media channels.

Dear Central Rockets,

Some people only dream of meeting their favorite musicians but I get to teach mine! I love you and miss you so very much. I can’t wait to sing and play together again soon, but until then remember that “we are Central Rockets watch us fly, fly, fly. We are taking learning to an all time high. What we use for rocket fuel is the learning that we do in school. We are Central Rockets watch us fly, fly, fly.”

Love,
Mrs. Harris

Ms. Hutton"

post_text: "Hi Kiddos! I read a quote recently. “Sometimes we’re tested, not to show our weaknesses, but to discover our strengths.” This is that time. We are all learning together, so don’t get discouraged. Let’s look for the silver linings (the good stuff). If you need someone, I’m here. Just reach out. Make sure to read, get exercise, and find a creative outlet that makes you happy every day. I sure do miss getting to see everyone’s face! Much love, Mrs. Cox"

post_text:
"To my 3rd graders,
I miss each and every one of you every single day! I’m sad we are not together, like we used to be, but dear friends ... I won’t cry because our year is over, I will SMILE because this year with you, happened in a very special way.
To paraphrase Dr Seuss, every single day I want you “to keep your eyes open enough, so you will learn, the most wonderful stuff”. You will be learning in very new and different ways, and “sometimes the questions will seem complicated but the answers just might be simple” because you have so many people here, just for you! And always “think and wonder... wonder and think”. “You’re off to great places ... today is your day ... your mountain is waiting ... so get on your way!”
Until we meet again!
Hugs,
Mrs. Venard"

To my students,

I want you to remember that I love you so much and I always will! I wish I had just one more chance to give you a big hug before you start at DCMS next year.
Here are some things I want you to remember as we finish out this year:

You can do anything because I believe you can.

You are special, unique, and loved NO MATTER WHAT.

Even though you are at home during this time, you still need to wear deodorant. Everyday.

Finally, you will always be one of “Mr. Austin’s kids”!

I love you very much! Be sure to invite me to your graduation! #Classof2027

Much love,
Mr. Austin

post_text:
"Callie (my silly cat) and I would like to remind our Ross Rhinos and all the kiddos in Dodge City to keep reading! Read with a flashlight, read a recipe with your mom or dad, read your favorite book, read signs while taking a walk, or read in a blanket fort...but keep reading! While we can’t travel in person, a book can take you to amazing places! Miss you all so much! Stay safe!!!"
❤️Mrs. Fairbank, Ross Librarian

Lights, Camera, ACTION! 2020 CENSUS - GET OUT THE COUNT VIDEO CHALLENGE
Students can unleash their creativity to create a video and potentially win a $10,000 student prize and/or a $30,000 grand prize. The challenge: Explain why the census matters in a short (30 seconds to 3 minutes) video, designed for a platform such as YouTube, that uses entertainment, emotion, creativity, and/or humor to motivate people to respond. Submissions are due April 17 th at 11:59pm EDT.

APRIL 1 is CENSUS DAY!

#EachKansanCounts! Respond to the 2020 Census at 2020census.gov or call 1-844-330-2020
“It is easier than ever to respond to the Census--online, by phone, or by mail—all without having to meet a census taker. Visit 2020Census.gov to complete the Census online or call (844) 330-2020 to talk to a live Census employee who can help you complete it by phone.”

The direct line for Spanish-speakers: (844)468-2020. Direct lines available in 12 other languages.

Staff, Parents, and Students - Today Governor Kelly issued Executive Order No. 20-16. According to KSDE and other state officials, this order does not alter plans for Continuous Learning. Packet pick up and grab and go meal distribution will continue as scheduled. Please remember that there will be separate delivery lines for packet pick up and grab and go meals. Your patience with traffic congestion is greatly appreciated.

Thank you!

Announcement from Dodge City High School

USD 443 Students, Parents & Guardians: If a student needs a Google password reset, please access the links on usd443.org to have the password reset. This link can be found on the opening page of usd443.org under the Continuous Learning tab at the top of the page. A second link appears under Calendar—School Calendar—Dodge City High School. This second link is a tab at the top of the DCHS Calendar page. Both links will connect you with a Google Form. Complete the information on this form and submit. A USD 443 employee will reset the password within ½ day.

Important Message
On March 17, Governor Laura Kelly announced Kansas schools will be closed and cease in-person instruction as we know it through May 31, 2020. SCHOOL WILL CONTINUE, but it will be different. There will be no delivery of instruction to students before Monday, March 30, 2020. Please watch your email and district website www.USD443.org for instructions about continued learning.

post_text:
We are super excited and super proud to announce that Mr. Justin Heeke, Seventh-Grade Physical Education Teacher at Comanche Middle School, was named to the 2020 Class of Kansas Master Teachers.

Mr. Heeke joins a group of seven teachers across the state who will be honored on Master Teacher Day to be held Wednesday, April 1 at Emporia State University.

Emporia State established the Kansas Master Teacher awards in 1954. The awards are presented annually to selected teachers who demonstrate the attributes of exemplary professional educators.

Dodge City Public Schools added 5 new photos — in Dodge City, Kansas.
February 25 at 2:31 PM · Dodge City, KS ·

7th grade students created these expressive graffiti portraits in the style of street artist Jean-Michel Basquiat, using pre-painted tag board, tempera paints and oil pastels. Basquiat grew famous during the 80s as an expressionist and hung out with famous people such as Andy Warhol. Although he became wildly rich quickly, he states that he could not even hail a cab in New York due to the color of his skin. Jean-Michel had an untimely passing at the age of 27 due to addiction. Basquiat's art has topped the biggest sale for individual art sold, surpassing Warhol's. His latest piece, "Untitled" recently sold for $111,000.000 to a private person in Japan.

Dodge City Public Schools added 3 new photos — in Dodge City, Kansas.
February 25 at 2:25 PM · Dodge City, KS ·

8th grade students created art using Clementine Hunter Zinnias style using tempera paint and chalk pastels. She was a self-taught artist and known as a folk artist. She was asked to put her work on exhibit, but she was unable to attend her own show, due to her being black. Ms. Hunter was sneaked into the show at midnight so she could view her work. She sold her work for 25 cents each, today, her paintings are worth millions.
